You can achieve this by telling Jackson
that you want the `Duration durationOfEvent` property
to be serialized by your own serializer.
You do this by adding a [`@JsonSerialize` annotation][1] to 
the property in your class `SomeEvent`.

	@JsonSerialize(using = MyDurationSerializer.class)
    private Duration durationOfEvent;

You can implement your serializer as a very simple
subclass of [`JsonSerializer`][2] which just gets 
the milliseconds and writes it as a JSON number.

    public class MyDurationSerializer extends JsonSerializer&lt;Duration&gt; {
    
        @Override
        public void serialize(Duration value, JsonGenerator gen, SerializerProvider serializers) throws IOException {
            long milliseconds = value.toMillis();
            gen.writeNumber(milliseconds);
        }
    }


---

Another simpler way is to use Jackson&#39;s `DurationSerializer` and
configure it with `@JsonFormat` to your desired output format.

    @JsonSerialize(using = DurationSerializer.class)
    @JsonFormat(shape = JsonFormat.Shape.NUMBER_INT,
                without = JsonFormat.Feature.WRITE_DATE_TIMESTAMPS_AS_NANOSECONDS)
    private Duration durationOfEvent;

---

For both ways described above the JSON output will look like this:

    {&quot;durationOfEvent&quot;:500}

  [1]: https://fasterxml.github.io/jackson-databind/javadoc/2.9/com/fasterxml/jackson/databind/annotation/JsonSerialize.html
  [2]: https://fasterxml.github.io/jackson-databind/javadoc/2.9/com/fasterxml/jackson/databind/JsonSerializer.html

